{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1444832399,"nonce":"dvMjrgGIIIBkuyZEkUHnV8WG8zQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODA2NDUyMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/327#issuecomment-148064523"},"message":"I know, but there could be pitfalls. When I see the lengths in the manual, they probably do not represent genomic sizes of genes (247 to 3133 is quite small), but transcriptomic. If you stay stick to what they provide you can rule out any mistake introduced by your own implementation, because this requires scripting to get these lengths correctly. (Or those provided by featureCounts, but they neglect overlapping genes etc. which also might affect the provided lengths) Similarly, if you need these lengths for something else, why would you not have them made available via a datamanager.\nIt's not that I'm voting against what you propose, but I just like to see the possibilities before we take any action ;). It would also be possible to provide the lengths \"from history\" if there is no data-manager version available.\n\nAnother piece from the manual: \"However, because the process of fetching the length of every\ntranscript is slow and bandwidth intensive, goseq relies on an offline copy of this information\nstored in the data package geneLenDataBase.\"\nThe geneLenDataBase seems to be some kind of local cache of these lengths.","files":null}]}